Mashamba had to drop out of school but the girls stayed, thanks to other people’s contributions. They take about 20 minutes to walk from school to home.

“Both classes are my second, classes are everything for me to have hope for myself as well as other members of the family,” Abigael Semama, 18, a second year student at the local public secondary school. “School is the only source of knowledge in my community. It’s the only way to bring water to the village.”

“We share everything we have in the family,” Abigael left school when she was 13-years-old for a year, “It was a worrying experience but I am glad that together with your support I am back picking up from where I have stopped. My parents were having some financial challenges. My father was deeply in debts after spending around 9 years in the area of khat cultivation. It appears Khat is what is running their lives.”

Her friends in the village have never had opportunity to attend school. One is Abdi Noor back in Somalia. “They told me that their parents said they don’t have money to send their kids to school.”

They talk about the children of former wife of the village leader, the Sudi Chief. Not only do they have so much, they have access to computers, smart boards and high fives boys from the local college stop by to train them on using computers.
